WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.600 --> 00:00:04.800
A program begins as a few lines of source code — and unfolds into something huge and detailed.

2
00:00:04.800 --> 00:00:09.000
Here's an honest question, not a claim: could reality work the same way?

3
00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:14.500
Could the rules of our universe be the output of something tiny — compiled, not chosen?

4
00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:19.600
Let's look at where that idea leads — and how it could fail.

5
00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:24.500
Start at the end — with what this one idea actually produces.

6
00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:31.000
Almost the whole Standard Model — our rulebook for every known particle and force:

7
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:37.000
the forces, why matter comes in three families, the single Higgs, the masses, how they mix.

8
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Gravity — Einstein's equation, with its constants fixed instead of assumed.

9
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:49.500
Pieces of cosmology — the early universe, how much ordinary matter there is, dark energy.

10
00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:56.000
The strength of light — the famous one over one-thirty-seven — is just one line among many.

11
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:04.600
And twenty-three concrete, testable predictions. That's the output. The real question: from how much input?

12
00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:09.500
Here's the surprising part: almost nothing goes in.

13
00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:15.500
Two numbers. A tempo — set by the edge of space. And a width: how many slots the building block has — five.

14
00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:22.000
And those two aren't even truly free. Strip it down, and what's left is one small whole-number pattern — and π.

15
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:28.000
A huge, detailed result from a tiny source.

16
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.600
That gap — between almost nothing and all of this — is the whole story.

17
00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:40.000
How can two numbers carry that much? Because they don't just get plugged in —

18
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.500
they have to pass a test.

19
00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:50.500
The parts they build must fit into one rigid mathematical object: E₈.

20
00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:57.500
E₈ isn't a force of nature. It's a proof layer — the referee that certifies the pieces fit only one way.

21
00:01:57.500 --> 00:02:04.000
Two hundred and forty points, one perfect pattern.

22
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:14.200
If anything were off, nothing would lock. Most possible universes simply don't compile.

23
00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:20.500
Now turn it around. If the proof closes for only one tempo and one width…

24
00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:26.500
…then the proof decides them. The inputs are forced by the structure they build.

25
00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:33.000
The thing works out its own starting point. The loop closes on itself.

26
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.500
That's the fixed point the theory is named after.

27
00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:44.600
Not a model you tune until it fits — a structure that has to be what it is.

28
00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:51.500
Once you see it, the elegance is hard to miss.

29
00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:58.500
The same small numbers — two, three, five — run through every part, because it's all one object.

30
00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:05.000
And it isn't frozen. A simple clock gives the whole thing a single resting state.

31
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:14.600
So the constants aren't dialled in by hand — they're where it settles. Almost no free choices, one connected picture.

32
00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:20.500
Now the fair objection: small whole numbers that fit reality —

33
00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:24.500
isn't that just numerology, like seeing faces in clouds?

34
00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:31.000
We took it seriously. Nobody drew this picture top-down. It assembled itself —

35
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:38.000
out of hundreds of small, independent checks, each verified by computer, that slowly clicked into one whole.

36
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:45.500
E₈ proves the pieces can fit. These checks prove we're not fooling ourselves —

37
00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:51.500
every load-bearing claim machine-verified twice, with a team tasked to break it.

38
00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:58.000
We froze predictions before the data, then ran two hundred thousand random look-alikes.

39
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.600
They get at most five right; this gets all thirteen. By luck? Below one in 10³⁰ — effectively zero.

40
00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:11.500
It isn't finished, and we don't pretend it is.

41
00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:18.000
One theorem from sealing the core; a few bridges to known physics; one unit no pure number can give.

42
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.600
Every gap is labelled — and it's killable: neutrino mass, proton decay, dark energy. One miss, and it's wrong.

43
00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:30.000
So — is reality compiled? We don't know. That's the honest answer.

44
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.500
But there's now a version you can test: built from almost nothing, fitting a surprising amount,

45
00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:40.500
with every gap marked and every test named.

46
00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:45.000
Maybe the constants were never arbitrary. Maybe they simply had to add up.

